properties.description: A large neighborhood developed in the mid-1950s, Polk Terrace was marketed to World War II veterans.

properties.name: Preston Hollow
properties.description: Preston Hollow, originally a separate town that was incorporated into the City of Dallas in 1945, is a neighborhood of 4000 homes with unusually large lot sizes north of the Park Cities.

properties.name: Preston Hollow North
properties.description: Preston Hollow North is a neighborhood of about 1200 single family homes dating primarily from the late twentieth century about one square mile just north of the original town of Preston Hollow.

properties.name: Prestonwood Estates West
properties.description: Prestonwood Estates West is a neighborhood of homes and apartments dating primarily from 1970s and 80s above the I-635 loop.

properties.name: Preston Trail
properties.description: Preston Trail is a neighborhood of homes dating primarily from 1970s, 80s, and 90s with lots a minimum of one acre. The homeowners association was formed in 2005, after three groups merged.

properties.name: Prestonwood
properties.description: Prestonwood is a neighborhood of over 1,000 homes dating primarily from the 1970s and 80s. There is a PID, renewed in 2004, for the area.

properties.name: Prestonwood East
properties.description: Prestonwood East is a neighborhood of about 500 single family homes dating primarily from 1960s and 70s.

properties.name: Valley View
properties.description: Valley View is a neighborhood of single family homes in just north of the LBJ Freeway. The homeowners association was founded in 1976.

properties.name: The Landmark
properties.description: The Landmark is a small subdivison of single-family homes southeast of the intersection of the Dallas North Tollway and President George Bush Turnpike dating from the 2000s.

properties.name: Floral Farms
properties.description: Floral Farms is an abandoned former neighborhood located just north of the McCommas Bluff landfill and west of Lemmon Lake. A segregated neighborhood of about 100 families developed in the 1940s and ‘50s, the area was prone to flooding and the City bought out all residents in the 1970s. The City hopes to redevelop the area into the Dallas Eco Business Park.

properties.name: Roseland
properties.description: A Dallas Housing Authority project built in the early 1940s, Roseland is a neighborhood of townhomes and apartment buildings adjacent to the Central Expressway.

properties.name: Prestonwood Estates East
properties.description: Prestonwood Estates East is a neighborhood of approximately 450 homes dating primarily from 1960s and 70s.

properties.name: Prestonwood West
properties.description: Prestonwood is a neighborhood of 665 single-family homes. There are six sub-associations within the homeowners association representing individual subdivisions.

properties.name: Ravinia Heights
properties.description: Originally the farm of Eli Sanger (of Sanger Bros. department store), Ravinia Heights was developed by Claude Cain from the 1920s through the 1950s.

properties.name: Reunion District
properties.description: Named for Reunion Tower, the observation tower built in 1978 that defines the site, the Reunion District also contains Union Station, the city’s primary train station, and the Hyatt hotel.

properties.name: Richland Corners
properties.description: Richland Corners is a small subdivision of single family homes developed in the the 1970s and 80s near the border of Dallas and Richardson.

properties.name: Webster Grove
properties.description: Webster Grove is a neighborhood of approximately 430 single-family homes developed in the early 1960s, south of the I-635 loop.

properties.name: Ridgewood Park
properties.description: Ridgewood Park is a small mid-twentieth century neighborhood just west of White Rock Lake. The neighborhood association was formed in 1996.

properties.name: Roland Hills
properties.description: Part of the post-war building boom, Roland Hills is a single family home addition constructed in 1949. The neighborhood is located just south of Cockrell Hill.

properties.name: Rolling Meadows
properties.description: Built in the early 1960s, Rolling Meadows is a subdivision of about 200 homes just south of Cockrell Hill.

properties.name: Rolling Trails
properties.description: Rolling Trails is a small neighborhood of single family homes built during the 1970s.

properties.name: Rose Garden
properties.description: Rose Garden is a 400 household neighborhood, which includes Lincoln High School, with homes dating from the 1930s onward.

properties.name: Shannon Estates
properties.description: Located between Love Field Airport and Greenway Parks, Shannon Estates is a neighborhood of single-family homes first developed in the 1930s.

properties.name: White Rock Village
properties.description: Developed by Fox & Jacobs on the site of the former White Rock Airport, closed in the 1970s, White Rock Village is a neighborhood of single family homes southeast of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Wynnewood Hills
properties.description: Wynnewood Hills is a neighborhood of approximately 120 single family homes built in the 1960s, 70s, and 80s that backs up against the Oak Cliff Country Club.

properties.name: Vickery Place
properties.description: Platted in 1911 by the Works-Coleman Development Company, Vickery Place is a neighborhood of about 1,500 homes adjacent to the Central Expressway. Vickery Place was made a City of Dallas Conservation District in 2006.

properties.name: Royal Highlands
properties.description: Royal Highlands is a small neighborhood of 213 homes developed in the 1970s directly south of the LBJ Freeway.

properties.name: Royal Hills
properties.description: First opened in 1955 and marketed as “luxury homes,” Royal Hills is a subdivision of nearly 300 homes in northwest Dallas.

properties.name: Royal Northaven
properties.description: Royal Northaven is a neighborhood of approximately 500 homes dating mainly from 1950s and 60s, just west of the Dallas North Tollway.

properties.name: Royalwood Estate
properties.description: Royalwood Estate is a neighborhood with about 800 homes dating primarily from the 1940s post-war housing boom to 1960s, just west of the Dallas North Tollway.

properties.name: Runyon Springs
properties.description: One of the largest middle-income housing developments in southern Dallas in decades, the neighborhood of single-family homes was developed on vacant land next to the Hidden Valley neighborhood beginning in 2001.

properties.name: Russwood Acres
properties.description: Developed in 1962, Russwood Acres is a neighborhood of 229 large homes adjacent to the Dallas North Tollway.

properties.name: Ruthmeade Place
properties.description: Established in 1905 and developed through the 1930s with Craftsman and Prairie bungalows, Ruthmeade Place is a neighborhood adjacent to I-35E with about 1000 homes and apartments.

properties.name: Shorecrest Estates
properties.description: Shorecrest Estates is an upscale neighborhood of almost 400 homes originally developed in the early twentieth century adjacent to Love Field. It has seen redevelopment since 2000.

properties.name: Elderwood
properties.description: Elderwood is a neighborhood adjacent to the Golf Club of Dallas developed in the 1970s by Bill Page. The neighborhood has two distinct sections: the “country homes” to the south and townhomes to the north.

properties.name: Preston Road Highlands
properties.description: Preston Road Highlands ia a subdivision of more than 300 homes and apartments dating primarily from the 1970s, 80s, and 90s.

properties.name: Fair Park Estates
properties.description: Fair Park Estates is a small neighborhood of single family and patio homes located near southwest of Fair Park developed in the 2010s by Southfair Community Development Corporation.

properties.name: Singing Hills
properties.description: A large subdivision opened in the late 1950s, the neighborhood experienced white flight in the 1960s and ‘70s and is now predominantly African American.

properties.name: Victory Park
properties.description: Victory Park is a new master-planned development running along the Stemmons Freeway. A total of 75 acres, the neighborhood contains such attractions as the American Airlines Center. Victory Park includes the Sports Arena TIF District.

properties.name: Skyline Heights
properties.description: The first project of developer Judson A. Crow, lots in Skyline Heights were first sold in 1924 for $1.50 down and $1.50 a month. The 145-acre neighborhood is on the west bank of the Trinity River.

properties.name: Coral Hills
properties.description: Coral Hills is a single-family development of more than 300 homes from Fox & Jacobs that opened in 1959.

properties.name: Southwestern Medical District
properties.description: The 387-acre Southwestern Medical District, located just north of the Stemmons Freeway, is a health care and research district that includes UT Southwestern Medical Center, Parkland Hospital and Children’s Medical Center Dallas as well as biotech companies.

properties.name: Sparkman Club Estates
properties.description: Established in 1958, Sparkman Club Estates is a neighborhood of more than 800 homes in northwest Dallas east of Harry Hines Boulevard.

properties.name: Stults Road
properties.description: Stults Road is a neighborhood of almost 800 homes primarily built in the mid-twentieth century, just east of Central Expressway.

properties.name: Summit Lawn
properties.description: Summit Lawn is a small neighborhood of about 200 homes that began as part of the post-war housing boom.

properties.name: University Terrace
properties.description: Established in 1954, University Terrace is just northwest of White Rock Lake. The Crimewatch was formed in 1998. As of 2009, University Terrace has a Neighborhood Stabilization Overlay.

properties.name: Uptown
properties.description: Gaining the name Uptown following the establishment of the Uptown Public Improvement District in 1993, this neighborhood originally contained the mansions of elite families, the Little Mexico neighborhood and one of the city’s first Freedman’s towns.

properties.name: Westmoreland Heights
properties.description: Primarily developed during the 1940s and 1970s, Westmoreland Heights is a neighborhood of mostly single family homes bordered by Tipton Park and industrial complexes.

properties.name: White Rock
properties.description: White Rock is a neighborhood of about 800 homes sitting on the west shore of White Rock Lake. The neighborhood association is one of the oldest in Dallas, having been formed in 1953.
